  "prompt": "What can I do if my new CA driver's license hasn't come in the mail?",
  "response": "Okay, here's a breakdown of what you can do if your new California driver's license hasn't arrived in the mail:\n\n**1. Check the Expected Delivery Timeframe:**\n\n*   **CA DMV Website:** The California DMV website (dmv.ca.gov) is the best source for information.  Look for information about processing and mailing times for driver's licenses.  They often have estimated timeframes posted, which can fluctuate depending on volume.\n*   **Generally:** Typically, it can take anywhere from **2 to 4 weeks** for a new or renewed driver's license to arrive in the mail in California.  However, this can be longer during busy periods.\n\n**2. Confirm Your Mailing Address:**\n\n*   **DMV Record:** The MOST important step is to confirm that the DMV has your **correct mailing address**. This is the most common reason for delays.\n    *   **Online:** If you have a DMV online account (created when you applied or renewed), log in and verify your address.\n    *   **Call DMV:** You can call the DMV's automated line or customer service line (see below). Be prepared to provide your driver's license number or other identifying information.\n    *   **In Person:** Visit a DMV field office (though this might take longer due to potential wait times).\n*   **If Incorrect:** If your address is incorrect, update it immediately.  This might require going in person or submitting a change of address form (available on the DMV website). Changing your address through USPS forwarding will not update your address with the DMV.\n\n**3. Track the License (If Possible):**\n\n*   **Confirmation/Receipt:** When you applied or renewed your license, you might have received a receipt or confirmation that includes a tracking number. Check your email or any paperwork you received.\n*   **USPS Informed Delivery:** If you have USPS Informed Delivery, you might see a notification about a piece of mail coming from the DMV. This can give you an idea of when to expect it.\n\n**4. Contact the California DMV:**\n\n*   **Online Contact Form:** The DMV website usually has a contact form or a section where you can submit inquiries.\n*   **DMV Customer Service Line:**  Call the California DMV's customer service line.  Be prepared for potential wait times. The number is (800) 777-0133.\n*   **Be Prepared to Provide:**\n    *   Your full name (as it appears on your application)\n    *   Date of birth\n    *   Driver's license number (if you have it)\n    *   The date you applied for/renewed your license\n    *   The address you provided to the DMV\n\n**5. Request a Duplicate License (if necessary):**\n\n*   **If it's been significantly longer than the expected timeframe (e.g., over 6 weeks) and you've confirmed your address is correct,** you might need to request a duplicate license.\n*   **How to Request a Duplicate:**\n    *   **Online:** You *may* be able to request a duplicate online through your DMV account (if you have one).\n    *   **Mail:** You can download and complete a Driver License or Identification Card Application (DL 44) from the DMV website and mail it to the address provided on the form, along with the required fee.\n    *   **In Person:** Visit a DMV field office. Be prepared for potential wait times.\n*   **Fee:** There is a fee for a duplicate license.\n\n**6. Consider Mail Theft/Loss:**\n\n*   **If you suspect mail theft:** Report it to the US Postal Inspection Service (USPIS).  You can find information on their website (uspis.gov).  While the DMV may not be directly responsible for mail theft, reporting it can help them identify potential issues.\n*   **If you suspect the license is lost:** Request a duplicate license as described above.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Temporary License/Interim DL:**  If you were issued a temporary license or interim driver's license (the paper one they give you at the DMV), it will expire.  Keep track of the expiration date.  If it's about to expire and you still haven't received your permanent license, contact the DMV immediately.\n*   **DL 44 Form:**  Keep a copy of the DL 44 form (Driver License or Identification Card Application) that you submitted.  It contains important information that you might need when contacting the DMV.\n*   **Be Patient:** The DMV can be busy, so be patient but persistent in your inquiries.\n\nBy following these steps, you can hopefully track down your missing driver's license or get a replacement issued as quickly as possible. Good luck!\n",
